## After the RMF — The Governance Foundation

Day 75 completed the OpenMRS system lifecycle — authorization through disposal, all seven RMF steps, from FIPS 199 categorization to secure decommissioning with archived patient records and destroyed encryption keys. That was 75 days of building and operating a specific security program for a specific system.

Day 76 begins a different kind of work. The next section of this project steps back from the system-specific RMF process and examines the governance foundations that make any security program function — starting with security policies. Policies are what the RMF assumes exist. Every time the SSP referenced an "organizational policy" for access control, incident response, or change management, it was assuming that policy had been written, communicated, and was being followed. This week, I want to think carefully about what makes a policy function rather than just exist.

I will be honest about where I am starting from: I have spent 75 days learning the RMF process, but policy writing is something I have mostly observed through the frameworks and templates I have studied rather than through direct professional experience drafting and implementing policies in an organization. What I have learned is that there is a significant gap between policies that satisfy auditors and policies that shape behavior — and the gap is almost always a writing and implementation problem, not a content problem.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Security policy is a topic covered in multiple frameworks — NIST SP 800-12 (organization-wide information security programs), NIST SP 800-53 (PL-1 through PL-4 policy controls), and the ISO 27001 policy requirements — but frameworks describe what policies should cover, not how to write them well. Today I focused on the craft of effective policy writing, using the OpenMRS access control policy as the working example, and thinking honestly about why so many security policies fail to accomplish anything.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified policy writing today is the distinction between a policy and a compliance artifact.

A compliance artifact is a document that exists to satisfy an auditor's checklist. It contains the right section headers, covers the required topics, uses the correct mandatory language ("shall," "must," "will"), and can be cross-referenced to a control framework. It was written by someone who studied other policies and produced a document that looks like a policy. It lives in a shared drive. Most staff have never read it. It is reviewed annually by the security team, minor edits are made to the revision date and a few paragraph tweaks, and it is re-approved.

A policy is a governance document that exists to shape behavior. It was written by someone who understood both the security requirement and the operational context — who knew how the people subject to the policy actually work, what decisions they face, and what guidance they need to make secure choices without constant oversight. It is communicated through training and reinforced through the systems and processes that implement it. Violations are detected and addressed. When it needs to change because the operational context has changed, it changes.

The difference is not primarily in the writing — it is in the intent and the implementation. But writing matters more than it is given credit for, because a policy that cannot be understood cannot shape behavior regardless of how well it is implemented. The writing is the interface between the policy intent and the people it governs.

---

## The Policy Hierarchy — What Policies Are and Are Not

Before writing a policy, understanding where it sits in the governance hierarchy prevents a common mistake: writing a policy that is actually a procedure, or writing a procedure-level document and calling it a policy.

**Policy:** The authoritative statement of organizational requirements and expectations. Policies answer "what must be done and why." They are mandatory. They are approved by organizational leadership. They change infrequently — when organizational requirements change, not when implementation details change. Example: "All OpenMRS users must authenticate using multi-factor authentication."

**Standard:** The specific, measurable implementation requirements that operationalize a policy. Standards answer "how specifically the policy requirement must be met." Example: "MFA for OpenMRS must use TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) with a minimum 6-digit code and a 30-second validity window."

**Procedure:** The step-by-step operational instructions for implementing a standard. Procedures answer "how to perform a specific task." Example: "To enroll a new OpenMRS user in TOTP MFA: (1) Log in to OpenMRS admin console; (2) Navigate to Administration → Manage Accounts; (3) Select the user account; (4) Enable TOTP authentication and generate enrollment QR code; (5) Walk the user through scanning the QR code with their authenticator app; (6) Verify enrollment by requesting a test code from the user."

**Guideline:** Non-mandatory recommendations for best practice. Example: "When selecting an authenticator app, consider apps that support encrypted backup of TOTP credentials."

The SSP's control implementation descriptions operate at the standard and procedure level — they describe specifically how each control is implemented. The policies that underlie them operate at the policy level — they establish the organizational requirements that the SSP's technical implementations are designed to satisfy.

A policy that describes step-by-step technical procedures has mixed the hierarchy — the procedures will become outdated when the technical implementation changes, forcing unnecessary policy updates. A policy that is too abstract to establish any concrete requirement has failed to create governance — "the organization will maintain appropriate access controls" is not a policy that shapes behavior.

