## What This Policy Does That Boilerplate Doesn't

Comparing this to a generic access control policy template reveals what the organization-specific writing adds:

The 5-business-day notification requirement for internal role changes came directly from Finding M-004 in Day 71 — the gap that the quarterly access review identified. A generic template would never include this because it is specific to the operational gap this organization actually experienced.

The end-of-business-day account deactivation requirement for separated employees is stated with a named responsible party (IT Administrator) and a trigger (HR notification) — not just "accounts must be deactivated promptly," which is meaningless.

The minimum necessary standard is connected to the Role Authorization Matrix document, which creates a policy-to-implementation link. Someone reading this policy can find the specific role scopes without having to ask.

The quarterly access review requirement names both the responsible party (Health IT Manager), the input (ISSO-provided report), and the deadline (10 business days) — not just "access reviews will be conducted quarterly."

