## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The policy writing failure mode that most clearly illustrates why specificity matters is the **2017 Memorial Healthcare System HIPAA settlement ($5.5 million)**. The OCR investigation found that Memorial had access control policies requiring workforce members to access patient information only as needed for their job. But the investigation found that terminated employees' login credentials had been used to access patient records for more than a year after their separation.

The policy said the right thing. The gap was in the implementation — specifically, the account deactivation process was not reliably executed because the policy did not specify who was responsible, what the trigger was, or what the timeline was. "Accounts will be deactivated when employees leave" is a policy that fails under operational pressure. "IT Administrator must deactivate the OpenMRS account by end of business day of the employee's last day, upon notification from Human Resources" is a policy that either happens or produces a documented failure.

The Memorial settlement is not a story about a bad policy — it is a story about a policy that was written at the wrong level of abstraction for the operational environment it was governing. A policy that states the requirement without specifying the mechanism, the owner, and the timeline is a policy that depends on everyone always doing the right thing without being told specifically what the right thing is.

