## What I Am Still Thinking About

The policy I wrote today addresses the access control requirements that are within the ISSO's direct operational scope. But the most important policy statement — the 5-business-day role change notification — depends on behavior from department managers, who are not security staff and who have never been briefed on why this matters.

Policy governance requires communication and training, not just document publication. A policy that is approved and posted in the shared drive but never communicated to the department managers who are responsible for Section 3.4's notification requirement is not functioning policy — it is documentation that will produce compliance failures when those managers, acting in good faith on what they know about their own responsibilities, fail to make a notification they were never told they were required to make.

This is the implementation gap that I want to think more carefully about: the policy is written, but the governance cycle is not complete until the people subject to it know what it requires of them and have been given the tools to comply. For security staff, that means reading the policy. For department managers, it means a specific briefing that connects their actions (notifying HR and ISSO about role changes) to the security outcome (ensuring access levels stay calibrated to job functions) that the policy exists to protect.

Policy writing is step one. Communication and training is step two. Monitoring for compliance is step three. None of the three is optional.

